insert into `#__content` values ('70', '05/2007 - From the Desk of Jerry Eslinger', '', '  <p style=\"text-indent: 0.3in\" class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><em><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;\">The Whole World in our Hands</span></em></strong><em></em></p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>One of the Apollo 17 astronauts said that, as he looked back upon the earth from the moon, the earth, spinning slowly against the vast, black background of space, looked like a &ldquo;big, blue marble.&rdquo; </span></p>    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Psalm 8 is a magnificent recounting of our being &ldquo;entrusted&rdquo; with the care of the earth. It reads: &ldquo;Yet you have made (us) little less than God, and dost crown (us) with glory and honor. Thou hast given (us) dominion (power, control, mastery) over the works of thy hands. Thou hast put all things under (our) feet. All the sheep and oxen, and also the beasts of the field, the birds of the air, and the fish of the sea, whatever passes along the paths of the sea. O Lord, our Lord, how majestic is thy name in all the earth!&rdquo;</span></p>', '<span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Alex Gondola, in his book, <u>Holidays are Holy Days</u>, asks us to think about this &ldquo;big, blue marble&rdquo; God has entrusted to us. It&rsquo;s old. Scientists estimate the earth is 4.6 billion years old. It has a solid core of iron and nickel surrounded by molten liquid. It&rsquo;s hot: somewhere between 1,000 and 3,000 degrees centigrade.</span>   <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>&ldquo;O Lord, our Lord, how majestic is thy name in all the earth!&rdquo;</span></p>   <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>But at the same time, two-thirds of its surface is cooled by water: 97 percent salt water, only three percent fresh. The oceans surrounding us cover nine times the surface of the moon. The earth below our feet is, in a sense, alive. Beneath the surface, twelve gigantic plates, some carrying continents, are constantly drifting and shifting. Sometimes they smash into each other. The earth quakes. Above us, polar jet streams, subtropical jet streams, atmospheric winds, El Nina, hurricanes with names like &ldquo;Bonnie&rdquo; and &ldquo;Charley&rdquo; are twirling and swirling and forming.</span></p>   <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>&ldquo;O Lord, our Lord, how majestic is thy name in all the earth!&rdquo;</span></p>   <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The earth reaches up to the peak of Mount Everest, 30,000 feet in the clouds, and down to the depths of the Dead Sea, 1300 feet below sea level. The &ldquo;big, blue marble&rdquo; is a marvel. It has tropical rain forests and bone-dry deserts, glaciers and grasslands, inlets and islands. </span></p>   <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>&ldquo;O Lord, our Lord, how majestic is thy name in all the earth!&rdquo;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial\">Gondola recounts how everywhere, the earth is bursting with a variety and richness of life, like a rhododendron blossom exploding into bloom. There&rsquo;s so much life. Like the Samoan dwarf goby, the world&rsquo;s smallest fish, so tiny each weighs just 1/14,000 of an ounce. Or the giant blue whale, that can grow to 150 tons and 110 feet long. The blue whale&rsquo;s tongue alone may weigh three tons, as much as 35 men. There&rsquo;s the smallest flowering plant, a floating duckweed so tiny 25 could fit on your fingernail, and the giant Sequoias of California, over 270 feet tall, and nearly eighty feet around. Each one has enough lumber to build forty houses.&nbsp; </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">But what have we done to God&rsquo;s good earth? We know. Already, half the rain forests are gone. Over 1,000 species are on the endangered or threatened species list in America alone. </span></p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Each year our country loses two million acres a year of prime farmland to erosion. </span></p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">&ldquo;O Lord, our Lord, how majestic is thy name in all the earth!&rdquo;</span></p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">I close with an excerpt from a letter from Chief Seattle to President Franklin Pierce, now nearly 150 years old: &ldquo;Continue to soil your bed and one night you will suffocate in your own wastes. Humankind has not woven the web of life. We are but the thread of it. Whatever we do to the web, we do to ourselves. All things are bound together. All things connect. Whatever befalls the Earth befalls also the children of the Earth.&rdquo;<span>&nbsp; </span></span></p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p> ', '1', '4', '0', '25', '2007-05-04 02:00:00', '62', '', '2007-05-04 14:49:18', '62', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2007-05-04 02:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'pageclass_sfx=\nback_button=\nitem_title=1\nlink_titles=\nintrotext=1\nsection=0\nsection_link=0\ncategory=0\ncategory_link=0\nrating=\nauthor=\ncreatedate=\nmodifydate=\npdf=\nprint=\nemail=\nkeyref=\ndocbook_type=', '2', '0', '5', '', '', '0', '0');
