insert into `#__content` values ('95', 'Interfaith Panel Discussion Addresses Climate Change', '', '<strong><span style=\"font-family: Arial; color: black\"></span></strong>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial; color: black\">The Interfaith Alliance of Colorado and Calvary Baptist Church are hosting an interfaith panel discussion on Global Climate Change at 11 a.m. Sunday, July 1 at Calvary Church, 6500 E. Girard Ave. (northeast corner of South Monaco Parkway and Hampden Avenue). Panel participants are the Rev. Peter Sawtell, Executive Director of Eco-Justice Ministries, Daniel Ziskin, Executive Director of Jews of the Earth, and Dr. Sherry Ellms, an Environmental Studies Professor at Naropa University. Jeremy Shaver, Director of Education and Family Ministries, will be attending this dialogue immediately after worship at Christ Church and would be willing to carpool.</span></p>  ', '', '-2', '1', '0', '1', '2007-06-30 00:25:56', '62', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2007-06-30 00:23:45', '2007-07-01 02:00:00', '', '', '', '1', '0', '9', '', '', '0', '0');
insert into `#__content` values ('93', 'Reclaiming Holy Ground', '', 'Eighty years old is what Moses was at this point. The man had already lived two lives in those eight decades. His first forty years were spent in ease and luxury as an adopted son of the Egyptian royal family. But those years in the palace had also been years of inner turmoil. This was because, even though his palace life was very nice, very easy, very secure, he was only there by a quirk of fate. He was a Hebrew by birth. And Hebrews were oppressed, exploited slaves in Egypt. ', 'As you can probably imagine, he had gone back and forth between feelings of deep gratitude for the sheer luck by which all had worked out so wonderfully for him, and, on the other hand,  being plagued by guilt and uneasiness over the terrible, glaring discrepancy between his own circumstance and that of his Hebrew brothers and sisters. The more he saw and knew of their life, the guiltier he felt. He wished, of course, that he could do something for his fellow Hebrews, but what could he do?\r\n    Then one day when he was almost forty, he came upon a slavemaster cruelly abusing a Hebrew slave. The moment seemed right to strike a blow for justice. So not only did he intervene, but he vented all of his pent-up guilt and frustration and killed the slave master. He buried the corpse in order to avoid Egyptian detection.\r\n    He assumed that at the very least, this would make him a hero among the Hebrew slaves –show them that he cared, that he was not without courage, and that he did have some social conscience. To his dismay it didn’t work that way. They saw him exactly for what he was: a hip-shooting, spoiled, wealthy, would-be liberal who was out dabbling in their problem mainly to assuage his own conscience. They angrily told him so the next day.\r\n    Poor Moses. Here he was, nearly forty years old and now without an identity. The murder, when it would eventually come to light, would bring to a quick and miserable end, his nice life in Pharoah’s palace. And now his own people (those ungrateful Hebrews) turned out to have no use for him either. The next day he hurriedly left Egypt, frightened, disillusioned and demoralized. His stab at saving the world didn’t work. Forget that, then. (On the way out of town he bought a copy of The National Review. He had just become a neo-conservative.)\r\n', '1', '14', '0', '31', '2007-06-15 12:38:20', '65', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2007-06-15 12:34:50', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', '1', '0', '1', '', '', '0', '0');
